 So would either of you like to talk about mailing lists?

45
00:01:41,460 --> 00:01:43,340
 - Well, I could talk a bit about fan history

46
00:01:43,340 --> 00:01:46,060
 and say that virtual fandom is a bit of an old concept

47
00:01:46,060 --> 00:01:47,740
 because fandom was always virtual.

48
00:01:47,740 --> 00:01:51,260
 It started as a way for people to keep in touch

49
00:01:51,260 --> 00:01:52,580
 with people all over the world

50
00:01:52,580 --> 00:01:54,620
 who shared this same weird interest.

51
00:01:54,620 --> 00:01:56,700
 What's happened here is that the rest of the world

52
00:01:56,700 --> 00:02:00,620
 has caught up with the sort of things that fans do

53
00:02:00,620 --> 00:02:04,780
 rather than fans necessarily changing what they do.

54
00:02:04,780 --> 00:02:06,380
 So they're all over the world.

55
00:02:06,380 --> 00:02:08,980
 They're a pocket of science fiction fans,

56
00:02:08,980 --> 00:02:11,060
 keeping in touch in much the ways they always have done.

57
00:02:11,060 --> 00:02:13,940
 And a lot of those ways are through emailing lists

58
00:02:13,940 --> 00:02:15,660
 where somebody sends an email

59
00:02:15,660 --> 00:02:18,540
 and sometimes later somebody else replies

60
00:02:18,540 --> 00:02:21,420
 and confusion reigns.

61
00:02:21,420 --> 00:02:22,900
 - Confusion does often reign.

62
00:02:22,900 --> 00:02:25,180
 - Yes, well, I have a long-standing mailing list

63
00:02:25,180 --> 00:02:27,340
 of me and some fan-ish friends.

64
00:02:27,340 --> 00:02:29,060
 But actually what's happened is

65
00:02:29,060 --> 00:02:31,700
 that the mailing list traffic has dwindled

66
00:02:31,700 --> 00:02:34,900
 and being replaced with WhatsApp and Discord.

67
00:02:34,900 --> 00:02:36,660
 And in fact, what happened is we keep starting up

68
00:02:36,660 --> 00:02:39,420
 WhatsApp channels whenever we're at a convention

69
00:02:39,420 --> 00:02:41,700
 in order to coordinate sensible things like eating

70
