00:03:27,060 --> 00:03:30,180
 and it's reasonably low traffic at the moment.

91
00:03:30,180 --> 00:03:32,060
 I don't know what they're planning to do with it,

92
00:03:32,060 --> 00:03:34,420
 but I will put a link in the show notes.

93
00:03:34,420 --> 00:03:36,020
 Are you on a Discord, Alison?

94
00:03:36,020 --> 00:03:37,820
 Have you been doing much Discording?

95
00:03:37,820 --> 00:03:39,860
 - I have not been doing much Discording,

96
00:03:39,860 --> 00:03:41,460
 but I am on many Discord.

97
00:03:41,460 --> 00:03:43,540
 So what I find with Discord is that

98
00:03:43,540 --> 00:03:46,020
 I'll be doing something, some activity

99
00:03:46,020 --> 00:03:48,420
 and a Discord will pop up around that.

100
00:03:48,420 --> 00:03:50,980
 And for a while we will have a flurry in activity

101
00:03:50,980 --> 00:03:52,100
 and it will be very useful,

102
00:03:52,100 --> 00:03:54,260
 but I'm not using Discord at the moment

103
00:03:54,260 --> 00:03:56,740
 for any part of my social life, I don't think.

104
00:03:56,740 --> 00:03:59,140
 I do use Slack a bit

105
00:03:59,140 --> 00:04:00,820
 when we're talking about things like that

106
00:04:00,820 --> 00:04:03,100
 for a group of people who I work with.

107
00:04:03,100 --> 00:04:05,220
 So it's not necessarily a science fiction or thing at all.

108
00:04:05,220 --> 00:04:08,540
 In fact, not, but that's only a social space,

109
00:04:08,540 --> 00:04:09,540
 not really a work space.

110
00:04:09,540 --> 00:04:11,500
 We talk about things like how to make money,

111
00:04:11,500 --> 00:04:13,340
 which at the moment is, yeah, don't.

112
00:04:13,340 --> 00:04:16,020
 - Yeah, we have a Discord and we have morning tea

113
00:04:16,020 --> 00:04:18,380
 or afternoon tea for people in the wrong time zones

114
00:04:18,380 --> 00:04:20,060
 every morning and that's really nice.

115
00:04:20,060 --> 00:04:22,900
 And for me, Slack is mostly a workplace,

116
00:04:22,900 --> 00:04:26,380
 so I don't usually check that outside the work day.

117
00:04:26,380 --> 00:04:28,060
 How are you finding Discord?

118
00:04:28,060 --> 00:04:30,780
 So you, a member of lots of Discords are only a couple.

119
00:04:30,780 --> 00:04:32,580
 - I remember only one Discord

120
00:04:32,580 --> 00:04:34,180
 because I think I'd previously assumed

121
00:04:34,180 --> 00:04:36,860
 it was sort of for gaming mostly,

122
00:04:36,860 --> 00:04:39,100
 but actually it's just like IRC,

123
00:04:39,100 --> 00:04:41,220
 which was a key part of my social life

124
00:04:41,220 --> 00:04:42,980
 in the pre-discord times,

125
00:04:42,980 --> 00:04:44,660
 except as much easier to spontaneously

126
00:04:44,660 --> 00:04:46,420
 have voice conversations with people.

127
00:04:46,420 --> 00:04:47,660
 So I'm really enjoying it, yeah.

128
00:04:47,660 --> 00:04:49,380
 And I use Slack only for work.

129
00:04:49,380 --> 00:04:51,900
 So it's nice to keep that division of Slack is for work.

130
00:04:51,900 --> 00:04:54,700
 Discord is for non-work situation.

131
00:04:54,700 --> 00:04:56,340
 - Yeah, I think Discord and Slack

132
00:04:56,340 --> 00:04:58,620
 are very similar in some ways.

133
00:04:58,620 --> 00:05:02,100
 Discord started as a way of letting gamers do voice chat

134
00:05:02,100 --> 00:05:04,140
 and has kind of grown beyond that.

135
00:05:04,140 --> 00:05:07,020
 And Slack started as a way to let work colleagues

136
00:05:07,020 --> 00:05:10,140
 talk to each other in serious text conversations

137
00:05:10,140 --> 00:05:11,500
 and has grown beyond that.

138
00:05:11,500 --> 00:05:14,340
 And they have kind of slowly been moving towards the middle

139
00:05:14,340 --> 00:05:15,620
 from opposite directions,

140
00:05:15,620 --> 00:05:17,300
 which has been quite interesting to watch.

141
00:05:17,300 --> 00:05:20,860
 - The other big technology that has been used quite a lot

142
00:05:20,860 --> 00:05:23,060
 recently is Zoom.

143
00:05:23,060 --> 00:05:28,060
 So Alison, you have ran a first Thursday pub meeting on Zoom.

144
00:05:28,060 --> 00:05:31,660
 And I was curious to see what your thoughts about that were

145
00:05:31,660 --> 00:05:32,700
 and how it went.

146
00:05:32,700 --> 00:05:34,300
 - I think I should start by saying

147
00:05:34,300 --> 00:05:37,340
 there are a great many video conferencing options

148
00:05:37,340 --> 00:05:41,740
 and Zoom has emerged, I think pretty well everywhere

149
00:05:41,740 --> 00:05:45,060
 as having probably the best combination of ease of use

150
00:05:45,060 --> 00:05:49,620
 and ability to deliver quality audio and video

151
00:05:49,620 --> 00:05:52,300
 over quite small brand width in a lot of cases

152
00:05:52,300 --> 00:05:53,660
 for quite a lot of people.

153
00:05:53,660 --> 00:05:56,700
 So it's just got the sweet spot of the package.

154
00:05:56,700 --> 00:05:59,580
 I looked at, I wanted to run a virtual first Thursday meeting

155
00:05:59,580 --> 00:06:01,380
 for people who don't know that London fans

156
00:06:01,380 --> 00:06:03,380
 have been meeting on the first Thursday of the month

157
00:06:03,380 --> 00:06:07,260
 ever since 1946 in a variety of London pubs.

158
00:06:07,260 --> 00:06:09,420
 And we couldn't do it this month.

159
00:06:09,420 --> 00:06:11,780
 And so I thought it would be good to have a virtual thing.

160
00:06:11,780 --> 00:06:14,580
 And the people in the first Thursday Facebook group

161
00:06:14,580 --> 00:06:15,940
 thought that it would be quite a good thing.

162
00:06:15,940 --> 00:06:18,260
 So I set about exhaustively testing

163
00:06:18,260 --> 00:06:20,900
 every video conference a solution available,

164
00:06:20,900 --> 00:06:22,780
 try and find one that would help us do that.

165
00:06:22,780 --> 00:06:27,300
 And what I didn't want was something where the 50 or so people

166
00:06:27,300 --> 00:06:29,500
 who might turn up on a Thursday night

167
00:06:29,500 --> 00:06:32,420
 would all cram into one video conferencing space

168
00:06:32,420 --> 00:06:35,740
 and have it go, oh well, I can't have 50 people

169
00:06:35,740 --> 00:06:36,660
 all talking at once.

170
00:06:36,660 --> 00:06:39,900
 If you actually go to a real pub, you go and sit at tables.

171
00:06:39,900 --> 00:06:42,220
 And what happens at the first Thursday

172
00:06:42,220 --> 00:06:44,380
 is that people mostly go and sit at the same table

173
00:06:44,380 --> 00:06:45,220
 every time.

174
00:06:45,220 --> 00:06:48,780
 So there'll be a table that mostly has zed zed

175
00:06:48,780 --> 00:06:49,740
 and dyed people on it.

176
00:06:49,740 --> 00:06:52,540
 And there'll be a table that mostly has old farts on it.

177
00:06:52,540 --> 00:06:54,420
 And there'll be a table for people

178
00:06:54,420 --> 00:06:56,420
 who want to talk seriously about science fiction.

179
00:06:56,420 --> 00:06:59,020
 There'll be a table for people who want to smough the Eastergum.

180
00:06:59,020 --> 00:07:03,260
 And what we were trying to do was recreate some sense of that

181
00:07:03,260 --> 00:07:07,100
 in the zoo by using Zoom's breakout rooms

182
00:07:07,100 --> 00:07:09,780
 to essentially act as these tables.

183
00:07:09,780 --> 00:07:13,620
 And it turns out that video conferencing for business,

184
00:07:13,620 --> 00:07:16,940
 they don't think that people are going to want to move around

185
00:07:16,940 --> 00:07:19,020
 between the breakout rooms regularly

186
00:07:19,020 --> 00:07:21,020
 or dash away from their breakout room

187
00:07:21,020 --> 00:07:23,940
 because somebody started to be boring and nip off for a smoke.

188
00:07:23,940 --> 00:07:26,180
 Though actually I've been at work conferences

189
00:07:26,180 --> 00:07:27,340
 where that has been the case.

190
00:07:27,340 --> 00:07:29,540
 So it turned out to be quite complicated to set up

191
00:07:29,540 --> 00:07:31,780
 and I did it by getting a paid Zoom account,

192
00:07:31,780 --> 00:07:33,740
 making everyone in the meeting co-hosts.

193
00:07:33,740 --> 00:07:34,580
 And then after that,

194
00:07:34,580 --> 00:07:36,540
 they could move themselves around but to do these rooms.

195
00:07:36,540 --> 00:07:37,980
 We had no password.

196
00:07:37,980 --> 00:07:39,420
 Our security strategy was,

197
00:07:39,420 --> 00:07:42,180
 if anyone tries to do anything naughty, we'd boot them,

198
00:07:42,180 --> 00:07:45,500
 which is not the most elaborate security strategy.

199
00:07:45,500 --> 00:07:47,420
 And it worked fantastically and everyone had a lot of fun

200
00:07:47,420 --> 00:07:49,380
 and we had about 40 people or so

201
00:07:49,380 --> 00:07:51,300
 and we had a really good evening,

202
00:07:51,300 --> 00:07:55,900
 except mostly my fun was mostly the fun of sorting it all out,

203
00:07:55,900 --> 00:07:59,220
 which so it felt more like con-running type fun

204
00:07:59,220 --> 00:08:01,660
 rather than sitting around in a pub type fun.

205
00:08:01,660 --> 00:08:03,980
 But I have been having a lot of sitting around

206
00:08:03,980 --> 00:08:07,900
 in the pub type fun on many video conferencing services.

207
00:08:07,900 --> 00:08:10,700
 So I don't want to suggest that I'd be missing out on that.

208
00:08:10,700 --> 00:08:13,260
 The only thing I've missed out on is that the hangovers really

209
00:08:13,260 --> 00:08:15,980
 and tried to get back from London and the tube

210
00:08:15,980 --> 00:08:17,220
 at two o'clock in the morning,

211
00:08:17,220 --> 00:08:20,060
 having not entirely worked out what I was doing.

212
00:08:20,060 --> 00:08:21,300
 I've missed that.

213
00:08:21,300 --> 00:08:23,900
 There's no reason you couldn't recreate the hangover experience

214
00:08:23,900 --> 00:08:25,340
 in the comfort of your own home.

215
00:08:25,340 --> 00:08:27,300
 It turns out that there's a,

216
00:08:27,300 --> 00:08:30,260
 the amount I want to drink on Zoom

217
00:08:30,260 --> 00:08:34,420
 seems to be lower than the amount I want to drink in the pub,

218
00:08:34,420 --> 00:08:36,220
 which is quite good really.

219
00:08:36,220 --> 00:08:38,100
 I mean, we do have beer and it's quite nice

220
00:08:38,100 --> 00:08:40,420
 and we've been buying beer from local breweries

221
00:08:40,420 --> 00:08:41,260
 and that's good.

222
00:08:41,260 --> 00:08:43,260
 It's not quite such a drinking experience.

223
00:08:43,260 --> 00:08:44,780
 The beer is vastly better.

224
00:08:44,780 --> 00:08:48,820
 We had two notable groups of spies on our chat.

225
00:08:48,820 --> 00:08:52,740
 The first was the Yom's Vikings, trying to work out

226
00:08:52,740 --> 00:08:57,100
 whether this would be effective for a virtual Yom's thing,

227
00:08:57,100 --> 00:08:59,540
 which is a book discussion where traditionally

228
00:08:59,540 --> 00:09:01,780
 one person holds the speaking object

229
00:09:01,780 --> 00:09:03,500
 and speaks at any time.

230
00:09:03,500 --> 00:09:05,620
 And the first Thursday group,

231
00:09:05,620 --> 00:09:08,420
 the Vanguard group in Seattle turned up

232
00:09:08,420 --> 00:09:11,540
 to see whether they thought they would be able to run

233
00:09:11,540 --> 00:09:13,700
 a Seattle meeting using the same technology.

234
00:09:13,700 --> 00:09:15,620
 So it's kind of spreading.

235
00:09:15,620 --> 00:09:18,140
 - And I think it's worth noting that the Toronto Faddo

236
00:09:18,140 --> 00:09:19,700
 also has a first Thursday meeting,

237
00:09:19,700 --> 00:09:21,980
 which I think started because people from London

238
00:09:21,980 --> 00:09:24,140
 went over to Toronto and introduced it.

239
00:09:24,140 --> 00:09:26,820
 So I think it is not an accident that is the same day.

240
00:09:26,820 --> 00:09:28,500
 But it's kind of nice to think that there are fans

241
00:09:28,500 --> 00:09:30,620
 all over the world who meet on a first Thursday.

242
00:09:30,620 --> 00:09:32,300
 One of the reasons I didn't come to the first Thursday

243
00:09:32,300 --> 00:09:34,100
 is 'cause I don't usually come to the first Thursday

244
00:09:34,100 --> 00:09:37,140
 and I thought going along, if everyone who doesn't usually go

245
00:09:37,140 --> 00:09:39,460
 had clicked on the button, I was a bit worried

246
00:09:39,460 --> 00:09:40,420
 it would get overwhelmed.

247
00:09:40,420 --> 00:09:41,980
 So I did not go.

248
00:09:41,980 --> 00:09:43,660
 - In practice, it was fine.

249
00:09:43,660 --> 00:09:46,460
 But also one of the things that happened on Thursday

250
00:09:46,460 --> 00:09:50,220
 was that we got some people who have been to the first Thursday

251
00:09:50,220 --> 00:09:52,740
 from time to time, but because they live in Australia

252
00:09:52,740 --> 00:09:56,260
 or Canada or Seattle or wherever,

253
00:09:56,260 --> 00:09:58,260
 do not habitually get to it.

254
00:09:58,260 --> 00:10:01,340
 And in that included at least one regular

255
00:10:01,340 --> 00:10:02,740
 who's just moved to New Zealand.

256
00:10:02,740 --> 00:10:04,380
 So obviously it was very nice to see them.

257
00:10:04,380 --> 00:10:06,300
 The other group of people who got there

258
00:10:06,300 --> 00:10:09,340
 were people who would love to go to the first Thursday

259
00:10:09,340 --> 00:10:11,180
 and who are London fans,

260
00:10:11,180 --> 00:10:14,020
